Waynautic's AI QA Agent integrates with Exgenix to transform QA governance for stock exchanges, providing intelligent test case generation, comprehensive traceability, and real-time insights across the entire testing lifecycle.

The AI QA Agent connects directly to JIRA/ADO, eliminating manual effort in requirement management: Automatic Sync: Requirements flow seamlessly from JIRA/ADO into the AI QA Agent with a single click Zero Data Loss: No manual copy-paste operations required Real-World Example: Surveillance use case monitoring unusual trading patterns demonstrated in the video Instant Access: Requirements appear in the agent interface immediately after sync info Business Impact: Eliminates data entry errors and reduces requirement import time from hours to seconds.

Domain-trained AI models generate comprehensive test cases automatically: Exchange-Tuned Models: Specialized AI trained specifically for financial trading environments Bulk Generation: Select one or multiple requirements for simultaneous test case creation Instant Results: Complete test cases generated in seconds, not hours or days Intelligent Analysis: AI understands exchange-specific workflows and business logic info Business Impact: Reduces test case design effort by 80%, enabling QA teams to focus on execution rather than documentation.

Each generated test case includes: Clear Descriptions: Business-focused explanations of test objectives Step-by-Step Execution Flow: Detailed test steps with expected outcomes Tailored Test Data: Exchange-specific data aligned with trading workflows Comprehensive Coverage: Positive, negative, and edge case scenarios info Business Impact: Ensures consistent test quality and complete coverage across all functional areas.

QA teams maintain full control with flexible review options: Individual Review: Accept or reject each test case independently. Bulk Actions: Accept or reject entire test suite at once. Feedback Loop: Every decision trains the AI model for continuous improvement. documents.t: Step Settings​ For each step, configure the following: Description​ Brief explanation of what this step does Example: "Submit new order with limit price" Session​ Specify the session identifier for this step. Session Types: Session Type Description Use Case Continuous (Same Session) All steps use the same session Standard workflow where all operations belong to one session Different Sessions Each iteration uses a new session Session isolation or multi-user scenarios note Configuration Notes: Enter a session identifier (e.g., session1, session2) Steps with the same identifier share session context Captured variables (session IDs, tokens) are shared within a session Session Configuration 🖱️ Click to expand image Wait Time (seconds)​ Delay before executing this step. Use Cases: 0 seconds – Immediate execution 1–5 seconds – Short processing delays 5+ seconds – Asynchronous operations / market data updates Datasheet Selection​ Associate a datasheet with the step. For Individual API Steps: Open the datasheet dropdown Select an available datasheet for that API Datasheet values populate fields at runtime Datasheet Configuration Modal 🖱️ Click to expand image For Test Action Unit Steps: Click Configure A modal lists all APIs within the unit Select a datasheet and row number for each API Save configuration Datasheet Configuration Modal 🖱️ Click to expand image Pattern (Datasheet Row Usage)​ Controls how datasheet rows are consumed during execution. Pattern Behavior Use Case SAME_ROW Uses the same row for all iterations Retry logic, idempotency testing, consistent data NEXT_ROW Advances to next row per iteration Varied data, multi-scenario, load testing Iteration Examples NEXT_ROW (3 iterations): Iteration 1 → Row 1 Iteration 2 → Row 2 Iteration 3 → Row 3 SAME_ROW (3 iterations): Iterations 1–3 → Row 1 Pattern Configuration 🖱️ Click to expand image Row No. (Starting Row)​ Specifies which row from the datasheet to start with. Usage: Row 1 – Start at base row Row 2+ – Skip to a specific row Examples Start at Row 1: Uses base configuration Start at Row 3: Skips the first two rows, useful for specific test scenarios On Error (Error Handling)​ Defines what happens when a step fails. Option Behavior Use Case Continue Log error; proceed to next step Non-critical steps Abort Stop execution immediately Critical failures Retry Retry failed step (configurable) Transient/network issues tip Best Practices: Use Abort for critical steps: Login, Authentication, Order Acceptance Use Continue for optional operations: Notifications, Non-critical subscriptions Use Retry for network-dependent operations: Connection establishment, External API calls Error Handling Configuration 🖱️ Click to expand image

Pattern 1: Single Session for Entire Test All steps use the same session identifier: Step 1 (Login): session1 Step 2 (Order Request): session1 Step 3 (Order Response): session1 Step 4 (Logout): session1 Use Case: Standard workflow where all operations belong to one user session Pattern 2: Multiple Sessions Different steps use different sessions: Step 1 (User A Login): session1 Step 2 (User B Login): session2 Step 3 (User A Order): session1 Step 4 (User B Order): session2 Use Case: Multi-user scenarios, parallel user testing Pattern 3: Session Per Iteration Each iteration creates a new session: Iteration 1: session_${iteration_1} Iteration 2: session_${iteration_2} Iteration 3: session_${iteration_3} Use Case: Session lifecycle testing, load testing with isolated sessions

Strategy 1: Incremental Row Usage Step 1: Row 1, Pattern: NEXT_ROW Step 2: Row 1, Pattern: NEXT_ROW Step 3: Row 1, Pattern: NEXT_ROW Each step advances to the next row in its datasheet. Use Case: Testing with varied data across steps Strategy 2: Consistent Row Usage Step 1: Row 1, Pattern: SAME_ROW Step 2: Row 1, Pattern: SAME_ROW Step 3: Row 1, Pattern: SAME_ROW All steps use the same row throughout execution. Use Case: Idempotency testing, retry scenarios Strategy 3: Datasheet Synchronization Step 1: Row 1, Pattern: NEXT_ROW (Request) Step 2: Row 1, Pattern: SAME_ROW (Response - validates request) Step 3: Row 1, Pattern: NEXT_ROW (Next Request) Synchronize request-response pairs while advancing requests. 1. Suite Won’t Execute Causes: No test cases added Invalid test suite configurations Missing datasheets Connectivity issues Fix: Add at least one test case Validate each test case configuration Ensure datasheets exist and are linked Verify system/network connectivity 2. Parallel Execution Failures Causes: Resource contention Shared/locked data Infrastructure limitations Fix: Reduce level of parallelism Ensure test cases are fully independent Allocate additional resources if needed 3. Scheduled Execution Not Running Causes: Misconfigured schedule System maintenance window Missing permissions Scheduler errors Fix: Recheck schedule configuration Verify system/service status Confirm user or system permissions Review scheduler logs for errors 4. Reports Not Generated Causes: Interrupted execution Storage limitations Report generation error Fix: Allow tests to finish fully Free up storage or increase quota Contact support if issue persists
